	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EU outlines next phase of ACP banana support</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 December 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In a revised Communication to the European Council and Parliament, the Commission has outlined its plans for the next phase of support to established ACP banana exporters. Labelled the ‘Banana Accompanying Measurements’ (BAM), the support is needed to help ACP countries adjust to increased competition on the European market from other exporters, notably those in Central and South America.</p><p>Like the two preceding phases of support (the Special System of Assistance 1994-1999, and the Special Framework of Assistance 1999-2008), it has been made necessary by the reduction in EU tariffs on bananas from non-ACP sources. This was occasioned, in turn, by a series of adverse rulings against the EU in the GATT and WTO brought by Latin American exporters and also the USA (on behalf of one of its fruit companies). This led to the abandonment of a system in which ACP exporters were guaranteed a market for their fruit in their traditional markets of UK, France and Italy. It was replaced by a system in which traditional levels of ACP fruit (which entered the European market tariff free) had a price advantage over their competitors which paid a tariff. But this price advantage has been reduced progressively, thus putting pressure on the ACP.</p><p>The BAM has been designed in the light of the latest cut in EU tariffs on competing bananas (from €176 per tonne to €114 over a period of seven to nine years). Consequently, ACP exporters will either need to become more competitive (to allow them to cut their prices by up to €62 per tonne) or diversify into other products. The Central Organisation of Pineapple and Banana Producers and Exporters (OCAB) in Côte d’Ivoire has already sounded an alarm at the falling prices in France. It claims that they no longer cover the cost of production.</p><p>The BAM has a budget of €190 million over four years (2010-2013) plus a possible additional €10 million drawn from the annual EU budget. Available to 10 ACP countries that have supplied more than 10,000 tonnes of bananas to the EU on average over the last 10 years (Belize, Cameroon, Côte d’Ivoire, Dominica, Dominican Republic, Ghana, Jamaica, Saint Lucia, Saint Vincent &amp; the Grenadines, and Suriname), it is designed to assist the more competitive countries to adapt to these developments in the long term, and to help the others reduce their vulnerability by developing new (alternative or complementary) areas to generate income. An additional aim is to address the broader impact of adaptation on employment, education and healthcare, land use and the environment.</p><p>In Jamaica, for example, 80 farmers in seven north St Catherine communities have been selected as beneficiaries of a $43-million project funded under the current EU banana support programme to improve production and marketing strategies and provide new infrastructure, including the construction of five greenhouses on selected farms. A newspaper editorial reports on ‘renewed hope [for] farmers who saw their livelihoods disappear’, and on the ‘positive buzz’ around the crop diversification strategy, but calls on the Jamaican government to promote these projects as a sustainable farming model for smallholder agriculture in the country, and for a ‘robust rejuvenation of the “eat what you grow” campaign’.</p><p>The BAM support comes at a vital time, as a number of Caribbean states, including St Lucia, Dominica, and St Vincent &amp; the Grenadines, now have to rebuild a devastated agricultural sector following severe recent hurricane damage.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
